l name for someone who lived or worked at a manor house, from Old French <i>salle</i> ‘large room, hall’. Compare   Desalle   and   Lasalle  .","French (<b>Sallé</b>): from Old French <i>salé</i> ‘salty, salted’, hence a metonymic occupational name for someone who dealt with salt meat or salt fish, or perhaps, in a figurative sense, a nickname for a witty or mordant person. Compare   Sallee   and   Salley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Desalle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Marco, Reno.","Americanized form (also <b>De Salle</b>) of Italian   Di Salle  .","French: shortened form of <b>Delasalle</b>, a variant, with fused preposition <i>de</i> and definite article <i>la</i> ‘from the’, of   Salle   1 ‘large room, hall’."]},{"name":"Sallee","meanings":["French (<b>Sallée</b>): variant of <b>Sallé</b> ‘salted, salty’ (see   Salle  ).","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]},{"name":"Salles","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Luiz, Ricardo, Ana, Armenia, Ernesto, Fabio, Francisco, Gustavo, Jaime, Luzia, Manuel.  French Andre, Emile, Jean-Luc.","French: variant of   Salle   1.","French: habitational name from (Les) Salles, the name of several places in various parts of France."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Salle Esquire was born in 1400, in Monkokehampton, Devon, England, United Kingdom. He married Salle in 1425, in Monkokehampton, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1400–":"1400–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1429–1523":"1429–1523","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1425":"1425","1523":"1523","1400":"1400","1429":"1429","1405":"1405","Monk Okehampton, , Devonshire, England":"Monkokehampton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","East Down, Devon, England":"East Down, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1400–":"1400–Kuollut","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1429–1523":"1429–1523","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1425":"1425","1523":"1523","1400":"1400","1429":"1429","1405":"1405","Monk Okehampton, , Devonshire, England":"Monkokehampton, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","East Down, Devon, England":"East Down, Devon, England"},"fr":{"1400–":"1400–Décédé","1405–Female":"1405–Décédée","1429–1523":"1429–1523","1400–Male":"1400–Décédé","1425":"1425","1523":"1523","1400":"1400","1429":"1429","1405":"1405","Monk Okehampton, , Devonshire, England":"Monkokehampton, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","East Down, Devon, England":"East Down, Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Salle Esquire est né en 1400, à Monkokehampton, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Salle en 1425, à Monkokehampton, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1400–":"1400–Verstorben","1405–Female":"1405–Verstorben","1429–1523":"1429–1523","1400–Male":"1400–Verstorben","1425":"1425","1523":"1523","1400":"1400","1429":"1429","1405":"1405","Monk Okehampton, , Devonshire, England":"Monkokehampt